The paper deals with the problem of optimal relay positioning in wireless networks, which is a topic that falls under the intersection of several sub-fields in computer science. However, the use of superposition coding and FDMA, as well as the focus on low-SNR networks, suggests that the paper is most likely to be categorized under Information Theory (cs.IT). The paper also deals with network optimization and graph theory, which are relevant to Networked Systems (cs.NI) and Social and Information Networks (cs.SI). The use of geometric algorithms and the focus on the 2D plane suggest that the paper may also be relevant to Computational Geometry (cs.CG) and Graphics (cs.GR). Finally, the paper's focus on flow optimization and cut-set bounds suggests that it may also be relevant to Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC).
